title: Grateful Dead Live at Henry J. Kaiser Convention Center on 1987-11-08
lineage: PCM Master, Sony PCM 601ES -> RME Hammerfall > Soundforge 4.5/CD Architect > CDR; Recording and Transfer: Sean Weber-small; EAC and minor edits by Bill Gardner; ; QC by
description: Iko Iko, Little Red Rooster, Stagger Lee, Mexicali Blues > Big River, West L.A. Fadeaway, The Music Never Stopped > Don't Ease Me In China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Looks Like Rain, Crazy Fingers-> Truckin'-> Drums-> Jam-> The Other One-> Stella Blue-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues, E: Touch Of Gray

reviews.review_text: Goin' Back to San Anselmo... This was my only Birthday show! It was a fantastic night with many friends that I have not seen in years. The band was fantastic! Everything was just right. The Other One rocked! Stella Blue was very intimate as we all held hands behind the board. Tom Thumb's Blues was a special treat!

Good Show... but the Rhythm Devils of DSO outshine this era of Kreutz/Hart on a nightly basis. 1st Set: We open with a festive "Iko," but the drumming is as bland as ever. "Rooster" is decent despite Bobby's god-awful slid'ing.' "Stagger" is a good choice, but played a tad too mildly. At least "Mexicali" is a good time. As is the dependable "Big River." My goodness, this recording is remote. "West LA" is professional but not stirring. "Music" adds tension to the mix, but it's a cheery, celebratory "Ease" that ends the set on an upbeat note.

2nd Set: About four minutes of tuning, the vibes are in place for a joyous "China." Some lyric gaffes aside, the music reaches a dynamic if not fully-pronounced pitch during its latter moments. "Rider" is not all guns blazing, but is strong and spirited. Jerry's consistent slight riffing echoes through a touching "LLR." Jesus, Bobby...your screeching removes all semblance of emotional integrity from the version. A weak-jawed lilting "Crazy Fingers" pleasantly passes by. "Drums/Space" certainly convince at setting up an imposing-haunted mood. "OO" is expected...Not stratospheric so my brains are scrambled... but it's an extended '87 version at 9 minutes. Chimes add an extra ghastly effect to this downtrodden "Stella." A relatively short, at first tame, "Lovelight" closes out the set at reasonable frenetic pace.
A surprised ovation greets Phil front and center for a rare encore selection of "Tom Thumb's Blues." To be honest, I'm not sure when the last time they've played this tune. The perfunctory "Touch" is added as a reminder that 'if we all pull together, we may crack the Top Ten!" (They did, reaching #9)
3 1/4 stars

J Not sure what you are trying to say about the Rhythm Devils, I think every night they gave us something new. I really like the rhythm devils from the Frost in 83 Mickey uses some sort of sound bar that makes it sound as if a Big old Jet AIRLINER was about to land. Sorta of does it on this night but not the extent of the Frost 8 21 1983 if anyone wants to check it out there. I give the sound here a low score but the show itself I would give it 4 but to balance the scales I'll give it a 5 just because I want others to listen to it and not shy away from a 3 start performance. We are the ones giving out the starts so 5 cause I love the arena and the band.
